00:07:44.859 --> 00:07:47.400
FEMALE SPEAKER: Thank you all
for being here at Google today.

00:07:47.400 --> 00:07:49.250
We really appreciate it.

00:07:49.250 --> 00:07:51.630
Can you just take a minute
and introduce yourselves,

00:07:51.630 --> 00:07:52.700
and tell us your
character names,

00:07:52.700 --> 00:07:53.741
and everything like that?

00:07:53.741 --> 00:07:56.507
And if you're a director,
say that kind of thing well.

00:07:56.507 --> 00:07:57.340
MAX VON ESSEN: Sure.

00:07:57.340 --> 00:07:58.840
I'm Max Von Essen.

00:07:58.840 --> 00:08:00.620
I play Henri Baurel
in the show, who

00:08:00.620 --> 00:08:03.301
is part of a love
triangle of three men, who

00:08:03.301 --> 00:08:04.800
are all in love
with the same woman,

00:08:04.800 --> 00:08:06.675
or think they're in love
with the same woman,

00:08:06.675 --> 00:08:08.370
or want similar things.

00:08:08.370 --> 00:08:11.650
And he's actually only one
the main French characters

00:08:11.650 --> 00:08:12.150
in the show.

00:08:12.150 --> 00:08:14.410
So I'm a French
guy, kind of torn,

00:08:14.410 --> 00:08:17.415
I know I'm in love with
Lise, played by-- well,

00:08:17.415 --> 00:08:19.222
she'll tell you.

00:08:19.222 --> 00:08:19.930
I'm kind of torn.

00:08:19.930 --> 00:08:21.510
I desperately want
to be a performer

00:08:21.510 --> 00:08:23.593
and move to the United
States, and go to New York,

00:08:23.593 --> 00:08:26.880
and be a performer, perform
at Radio City Music Hall.

00:08:26.880 --> 00:08:29.660
But I know what my parents are
sort of gearing me up towards,

00:08:29.660 --> 00:08:31.160
taking over for the
family business.

00:08:31.160 --> 00:08:32.760
So he's very torn in his life.

00:08:32.760 --> 00:08:36.820
Torn as far as his
relationship with Lise,

00:08:36.820 --> 00:08:38.434
and his life in
general, as to what

00:08:38.434 --> 00:08:39.809
he feels he should
be doing, what

00:08:39.809 --> 00:08:41.428
his passion is to be doing.

00:08:41.428 --> 00:08:42.428
LEANNE COPE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:08:46.340 --> 00:08:47.580
MAX VON ESSEN: I'm not sure.

00:08:47.580 --> 00:08:49.231
LEANNE COPE: OK.

00:08:49.231 --> 00:08:49.980
Can you hear that?

00:08:49.980 --> 00:08:52.580
I'm Leanne Cope, and
I play Lise Dassin.

00:08:52.580 --> 00:08:56.890
She is the lucky
lady who has three

00:08:56.890 --> 00:08:59.820
men fall in love with her.

00:08:59.820 --> 00:09:03.670
She's a young girl who, she's
actually Jewish, and was

00:09:03.670 --> 00:09:06.205
hidden by the Baurel family
during the Second World

00:09:06.205 --> 00:09:07.150
War in Paris.

00:09:07.150 --> 00:09:14.810
So she comes out of hiding,
and she bumps into Jerry,

00:09:14.810 --> 00:09:18.760
who is kind of an instant,
love-at-first-sight thing.

00:09:18.760 --> 00:09:25.040
But she is also engaged to
Henri, so she's very torn.

00:09:25.040 --> 00:09:27.126
But there's a happy
ending in the end.

00:09:27.126 --> 00:09:28.750
I think, happy for
everyone in the end.

00:09:28.750 --> 00:09:31.083
Everyone figures out where
they should be going in life.

00:09:31.083 --> 00:09:33.790
So yeah, I play Lise Dassin.

00:09:33.790 --> 00:09:36.580
WILL BURTON: I'm Will Burton.

00:09:36.580 --> 00:09:39.180
I am playing Adam
Hochberg today.

00:09:39.180 --> 00:09:41.040
I'm actually an understudy.

00:09:41.040 --> 00:09:43.390
I cover him as
well, on some days.

00:09:43.390 --> 00:09:47.830
But Adam Hochberg is a
Jewish-American soldier

00:09:47.830 --> 00:09:50.770
who fought in World War II,
and decided, afterwards,

00:09:50.770 --> 00:09:56.010
to stay in Paris, and
pursue his writing career.

00:09:56.010 --> 00:09:57.580
He's a composer.

00:09:57.580 --> 00:10:02.220
So he's decided to stay
in Paris to be inspired.

00:10:02.220 --> 00:10:05.360
And his muse becomes Lise.

00:10:05.360 --> 00:10:07.800
He falls in love with Lise.

00:10:07.800 --> 00:10:09.560
And he meets these
two gentlemen,

00:10:09.560 --> 00:10:15.710
and they all become
buds, and that's

00:10:15.710 --> 00:10:17.885
kind of Adam's part to play.

00:10:17.885 --> 00:10:19.510
ROBERT FAIRCHILD:
I'm Robert Fairchild.

00:10:19.510 --> 00:10:23.600
I play Jerry Mulligan, the
role made famous by Gene Kelly.

00:10:23.600 --> 00:10:27.940
And he's a soldier
in World War II

00:10:27.940 --> 00:10:31.550
who stays in Paris on
the GI Bill to study art,

00:10:31.550 --> 00:10:33.670
and falls in love
with Lise, and becomes

00:10:33.670 --> 00:10:35.572
best friends with these guys.

00:10:35.572 --> 00:10:37.530
CHRISTOPHER WHEELDON:
I'm Christopher Wheeldon,

00:10:37.530 --> 00:10:40.550
the director choreographer
of "American in Paris."

00:10:40.550 --> 00:10:41.050
Thank you.

00:10:43.750 --> 00:10:47.130
I play this guy who is
happily choreographing

00:10:47.130 --> 00:10:50.210
in the ballet world, when
one day, a big Broadway

00:10:50.210 --> 00:10:51.670
producer came
along and said, hey

00:10:51.670 --> 00:10:53.650
do you want to direct
a Broadway musical?

00:10:53.650 --> 00:10:55.470
And I said, sure, why not?

00:10:55.470 --> 00:10:56.500
Let's have a go.

00:10:56.500 --> 00:10:59.610
That's my role.

00:10:59.610 --> 00:11:01.500
And I just-- sorry, Jill.

00:11:01.500 --> 00:11:03.730
I just want to say, Will's
actually making his debut

00:11:03.730 --> 00:11:05.560
tonight as Adam Hochberg.

00:11:11.264 --> 00:11:12.680
JILL PAICE: My
name is Jill Paice.

00:11:12.680 --> 00:11:17.940
I play Milo Davenport, who,
apparently, nobody loves.

00:11:17.940 --> 00:11:18.734
Thanks.

00:11:18.734 --> 00:11:20.150
CHRISTOPHER WHEELDON:
We love you.

00:11:20.150 --> 00:11:22.060
JILL PAICE: I'll take these two.

00:11:22.060 --> 00:11:25.060
She is a rich
American heiress, who

00:11:25.060 --> 00:11:28.360
arrives in Paris right at
the height of the new, sort

00:11:28.360 --> 00:11:30.830
of, art scene that's coming up.

00:11:30.830 --> 00:11:37.340
And she chases this guy
for most of the show,

00:11:37.340 --> 00:11:38.890
but also commissions
a ballet, which

00:11:38.890 --> 00:11:43.570
will star Lise, that Jerry
will do the set design for,

00:11:43.570 --> 00:11:45.640
and Adam will write
the music for.

00:11:45.640 --> 00:11:48.860
So I think I'm very important.

00:11:48.860 --> 00:11:51.187
And I love me.

00:11:51.187 --> 00:11:53.020
STUART OKEN: At the end
of the show, anyway.

00:11:53.020 --> 00:11:53.700
JILL PAICE: Yes.

00:11:53.700 --> 00:11:55.075
STUART OKEN: Hi,
I'm Stuart Oken.

00:11:55.075 --> 00:11:56.820
I get to play producer.

00:11:56.820 --> 00:12:00.630
I had the great good fortune
to be offered a chance

00:12:00.630 --> 00:12:05.320
to conceive of how
we might approach

00:12:05.320 --> 00:12:08.270
bringing "An American in Paris"
to Broadway, which had never

00:12:08.270 --> 00:12:08.770
been.

00:12:08.770 --> 00:12:12.580
It had only been this 1950 movie
that had been quite famous,

00:12:12.580 --> 00:12:15.880
but had never found
its way to Broadway.

00:12:15.880 --> 00:12:18.110
And it was a bit
of a dated movie,

00:12:18.110 --> 00:12:21.200
although there were lots
of wonderful things in it.

00:12:21.200 --> 00:12:26.190
So along with Chris and Rob
Fisher, our musical supervisor,

00:12:26.190 --> 00:12:28.650
and Craig Lucas, our book
writer, and of course,

00:12:28.650 --> 00:12:32.070
with the magnificent George
and Ira Gershwin songs

00:12:32.070 --> 00:12:34.680
to work with, we
had the good fortune

00:12:34.680 --> 00:12:39.380
to be able to spend the five
years it took to realize

00:12:39.380 --> 00:12:42.310
Chris's vision, with Bob
Crowley, and Natasha Katz,

00:12:42.310 --> 00:12:44.300
and his wonderful
team of designers,

00:12:44.300 --> 00:12:48.300
and then to have this amazing
company bring it to life.

00:12:48.300 --> 00:12:49.810
So we've had a
wonderful journey.

00:12:49.810 --> 00:12:51.320
And I'm proud to be here.

00:12:51.320 --> 00:12:51.820
Thank you.

00:12:55.889 --> 00:12:57.930
FEMALE SPEAKER: I'm going
to fall off this chair.

00:12:57.930 --> 00:12:58.400
MAX VON ESSEN: Are you OK?

00:12:58.400 --> 00:12:59.680
FEMALE SPEAKER: I really am.

00:12:59.680 --> 00:13:01.080
I don't usually wear heels.

00:13:01.080 --> 00:13:03.413
I don't know if you've bumped
into me around the office,

00:13:03.413 --> 00:13:05.786
but this is a special occasion.

00:13:05.786 --> 00:13:10.360
It's not working
out so well for me.

00:13:10.360 --> 00:13:12.260
So yes, you're here.

00:13:12.260 --> 00:13:16.000
You're playing at the Palace
Theater now, but you opened,

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:19.944
your world premiere was
in Paris, France, correct?

00:13:19.944 --> 00:13:21.610
Can you tell us a
little bit about that,

00:13:21.610 --> 00:13:23.909
how that came to be?

00:13:23.909 --> 00:13:25.700
STUART OKEN: That
usually comes back to me.

00:13:25.700 --> 00:13:27.575
I'll tell you a little,
and they can tell you

00:13:27.575 --> 00:13:30.110
what it was like to be there.

00:13:30.110 --> 00:13:31.890
You know, "American
in Paris," right?

00:13:31.890 --> 00:13:35.260
So you always have
to go somewhere.

00:13:35.260 --> 00:13:37.470
If you do a new musical--
and we are a new musical,

00:13:37.470 --> 00:13:38.969
even though it feels
like maybe it's

00:13:38.969 --> 00:13:42.200
not-- the first time it's
on stage, different script,

00:13:42.200 --> 00:13:45.230
different song order, different
people, different character

00:13:45.230 --> 00:13:48.570
conceptions, it's new, and
it takes you a lot of time.

00:13:48.570 --> 00:13:51.336
This is very different
than a revival, which

00:13:51.336 --> 00:13:53.460
you can kind of rehearse
and do, because you're not

00:13:53.460 --> 00:13:54.320
rewriting every day.

00:13:54.320 --> 00:13:57.080
Anyway, we needed to go
somewhere to work on the show,

00:13:57.080 --> 00:13:59.390
to, so to speak,
get the kinks out,

00:13:59.390 --> 00:14:01.780
but to really get our rhythm.

00:14:01.780 --> 00:14:05.070
And we had to pick
a place to go.

00:14:05.070 --> 00:14:07.800
And there was a wonderful
producer in Paris,

00:14:07.800 --> 00:14:09.710
his name is Jean-Luc Choplin.

00:14:09.710 --> 00:14:13.530
And Jean-Luc, who I
oddly happened to know,

00:14:13.530 --> 00:14:19.650
because we both spent 10 years
working at Disney between '93,

00:14:19.650 --> 00:14:21.820
I think, and 2004.

00:14:21.820 --> 00:14:25.790
And Jean-Luc has become
the artistic director

00:14:25.790 --> 00:14:30.220
of this exquisite theater, a
historic, beautiful building

00:14:30.220 --> 00:14:32.030
called Theatre du Chatelet.

00:14:32.030 --> 00:14:35.740
And France does not
have much of a history

00:14:35.740 --> 00:14:37.870
of doing American musicals.

00:14:37.870 --> 00:14:40.520
It's actually one of the
countries in the world

00:14:40.520 --> 00:14:43.280
where we just haven't
resonated with this very

00:14:43.280 --> 00:14:46.530
unique American art form.

00:14:46.530 --> 00:14:50.307
But Jean-Luc started bringing
productions in English

00:14:50.307 --> 00:14:51.265
that he'd put together.

00:14:51.265 --> 00:14:54.350
He'd only run them two or
three weeks at the most,

00:14:54.350 --> 00:14:58.580
but he'd bring in wonderful
performers and artists

00:14:58.580 --> 00:15:01.244
mostly from England,
because you do something

00:15:01.244 --> 00:15:02.660
in the original--
he only performs

00:15:02.660 --> 00:15:03.720
in the original language.

00:15:03.720 --> 00:15:07.040
So he was developing an
audience for American musicals,

00:15:07.040 --> 00:15:08.040
and he did the classics.

00:15:08.040 --> 00:15:09.329
He did Sondheim.

00:15:09.329 --> 00:15:10.620
He did Rodgers and Hammerstein.

00:15:10.620 --> 00:15:12.180
He did Lerner and Loewe.

00:15:12.180 --> 00:15:14.630
And after about six,
seven years of doing that,

00:15:14.630 --> 00:15:18.320
he thought that it possibly
was the time for his audiences

00:15:18.320 --> 00:15:20.870
to actually have a
brand new musical.

00:15:20.870 --> 00:15:24.020
But this seemed like a
rather safe one, because it

00:15:24.020 --> 00:15:25.970
had familiarity to them.

00:15:25.970 --> 00:15:28.960
The story had empathy
for French characters,

00:15:28.960 --> 00:15:30.530
and the music was so well known.

00:15:30.530 --> 00:15:35.370
So fortunately, serendipitously,
we managed to come together.

00:15:35.370 --> 00:15:37.400
And we rehearsed in America.

00:15:37.400 --> 00:15:39.450
It was our production
here in America

00:15:39.450 --> 00:15:40.840
that was all put together.

00:15:40.840 --> 00:15:42.870
And then all of it
went over to Paris,

00:15:42.870 --> 00:15:46.200
where the scenery
was all built there,

00:15:46.200 --> 00:15:48.320
the costumes were
all built there.

00:15:48.320 --> 00:15:51.030
And our whole company,
like 75 of us,

00:15:51.030 --> 00:15:54.020
lived in Paris for
3 and 1/2 months,

00:15:54.020 --> 00:15:56.350
and not only got
to make our show,

00:15:56.350 --> 00:16:00.190
but got to experience
the beauty and the joy

00:16:00.190 --> 00:16:04.500
of being in a location together,
and building the authenticity

00:16:04.500 --> 00:16:05.710
inside of our company.

00:16:05.710 --> 00:16:07.300
So that's how it happened.

00:16:07.300 --> 00:16:11.030
FEMALE SPEAKER: That sounds
absolutely fantastic.

00:16:11.030 --> 00:16:14.745
Now, some of you are from
New York, some of you

00:16:14.745 --> 00:16:15.880
are from elsewhere.

00:16:15.880 --> 00:16:19.600
Leanne, I know that you're
actually from England,

00:16:19.600 --> 00:16:22.010
and you were in the Royal
Ballet, is that correct?

00:16:22.010 --> 00:16:25.870
LEANNE COPE: Yeah, I'm from
a small town called Bath.

00:16:25.870 --> 00:16:27.842
Whenever I say that
here, they're like, what?

00:16:27.842 --> 00:16:29.720
You were born in a bath?

00:16:29.720 --> 00:16:30.870
Don't worry.

00:16:30.870 --> 00:16:33.700
It's a small town
southwest of London.

00:16:33.700 --> 00:16:36.310
But I moved to London when I
was 11 and studied at the Royal

00:16:36.310 --> 00:16:38.790
Ballet School, and then
danced with the Royal Ballet

00:16:38.790 --> 00:16:40.540
Company for 12 years.

00:16:40.540 --> 00:16:44.469
So ballet is silent art
form, so to suddenly,

00:16:44.469 --> 00:16:46.760
after 12 years of performing
on stage, to suddenly have

00:16:46.760 --> 00:16:48.660
to open my mouth
and speak and sing

00:16:48.660 --> 00:16:52.480
has been terrifying, but
liberating and amazing.

00:16:52.480 --> 00:16:57.507
So yeah, this is kind the
first venture into spoken word.

00:16:57.507 --> 00:16:58.760
FEMALE SPEAKER: Right.

00:16:58.760 --> 00:17:01.417
And it's your first
venture as well, correct?

00:17:01.417 --> 00:17:04.000
ROBERT FAIRCHILD: Yeah, I danced
with the New York City Ballet

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:06.450
in Lincoln Center, and I've
been there for 10 years.

00:17:06.450 --> 00:17:07.910
And that's how we met, actually.

00:17:07.910 --> 00:17:11.060
I've been in a lot of his
ballets at the company.

00:17:11.060 --> 00:17:13.690
And he asked me, can you sing?

00:17:13.690 --> 00:17:17.280
After we did some gala
where I was tap dancing.

00:17:17.280 --> 00:17:20.950
And I said yeah, I think so.

00:17:20.950 --> 00:17:24.034
And that's kind of how this
whole collaboration started

00:17:24.034 --> 00:17:24.950
between the two of us.

00:17:24.950 --> 00:17:30.180
And it's so liberating to
be on stage telling stories

00:17:30.180 --> 00:17:32.900
for 10 years, without
opening your mouth,

00:17:32.900 --> 00:17:37.106
and then to get the opportunity
to speak, and sing, and dance

00:17:37.106 --> 00:17:37.980
all at the same time.

00:17:37.980 --> 00:17:40.746
It's just the
coolest opportunity.

00:17:40.746 --> 00:17:43.370
FEMALE SPEAKER: Can you tell us
a little bit about the audition

00:17:43.370 --> 00:17:43.990
process?

00:17:43.990 --> 00:17:49.000
Because compared to the
sort of rock and roll,

00:17:49.000 --> 00:17:51.290
heavy movement shows
that have become

00:17:51.290 --> 00:17:53.980
popularized in
recent years, this

00:17:53.980 --> 00:17:57.860
is kind of a throwback to the
very classic days of Broadway.

00:17:57.860 --> 00:18:01.280
The big sweeping dance
numbers, it's beautiful.

00:18:01.280 --> 00:18:05.080
CHRISTOPHER WHEELDON: Well,
the audition process was tough.

00:18:05.080 --> 00:18:07.730
There are many reasons to do "An
American in Paris," of course.

00:18:07.730 --> 00:18:12.240
The great music of
George and Ira Gershwin,

00:18:12.240 --> 00:18:14.360
the phenomenal setting.

00:18:14.360 --> 00:18:17.190
But I think we all agreed
that unless we really

00:18:17.190 --> 00:18:23.300
found the cast that could handle
the dance in the show, really

00:18:23.300 --> 00:18:27.450
embody these characters,
and not just be-- there's

00:18:27.450 --> 00:18:30.540
a history of ballet dancers
having been on Broadway,

00:18:30.540 --> 00:18:34.570
and there tends to be a little
bit of a sort of, oh, you know,

00:18:34.570 --> 00:18:38.330
great dancers, but shame they
can't really sing or act.

00:18:38.330 --> 00:18:39.760
FEMALE SPEAKER: Right.

00:18:39.760 --> 00:18:42.600
CHRISTOPHER WHEELDON:
So we really wanted

00:18:42.600 --> 00:18:44.670
to find true triple threats.

00:18:44.670 --> 00:18:46.980
I actually call Leanne
a quadruple threat,

00:18:46.980 --> 00:18:53.660
because a triple threat is a
singer, an actor, and a dancer.

00:18:53.660 --> 00:18:56.340
But she also has to be a
ballet dancer, on pointe, which

00:18:56.340 --> 00:18:58.500
is a very specialized skill.

00:18:58.500 --> 00:19:03.010
So it made the search for
Lise particularly challenging.

00:19:03.010 --> 00:19:05.860
And I also work with
the Royal Ballet a lot.

00:19:05.860 --> 00:19:07.482
I'm artistic associate there.

00:19:07.482 --> 00:19:09.690
And so I've known Leanne
since she was in the school.

00:19:09.690 --> 00:19:11.930
And we actually grew
up in the same county.

00:19:11.930 --> 00:19:15.740
I was born about an hour away
from where Leanne was born.

00:19:15.740 --> 00:19:18.510
But I didn't know her
at that age, though.

00:19:18.510 --> 00:19:22.587
So somebody said,
we were searching,

00:19:22.587 --> 00:19:23.670
we were looking in London.

00:19:23.670 --> 00:19:27.230
We had an extensive
audition search

00:19:27.230 --> 00:19:29.260
all across the United States.

00:19:29.260 --> 00:19:31.020
And somebody said,
oh, well you know,

00:19:31.020 --> 00:19:33.510
Leanne Cope actually sung
once in the music competition.

