00:41:23.570 --> 00:41:26.160
Now there's secrets
that can't be exposed,

00:41:26.160 --> 00:41:29.110
so when Jerry learns
about her history,

00:41:29.110 --> 00:41:30.260
everything makes sense.

00:41:30.260 --> 00:41:33.450
But he doesn't know about
her, and those are things

00:41:33.450 --> 00:41:34.980
that really were differences.

00:41:34.980 --> 00:41:38.740
The big one is, you
said, moving from 1950

00:41:38.740 --> 00:41:40.870
to the moment the war ended.

00:41:40.870 --> 00:41:45.250
So the impact on every character
really is the war, right?

00:41:45.250 --> 00:41:49.080
It's about a lot of people
coming out of a very dark time,

00:41:49.080 --> 00:41:50.580
and actually, you
said this earlier,

00:41:50.580 --> 00:41:52.120
I think, Leanne,
or somebody did,

00:41:52.120 --> 00:41:56.080
that eventually, everyone
develops a sense of empathy

00:41:56.080 --> 00:41:57.580
for everybody else.

00:41:57.580 --> 00:42:01.580
They kind of get why they're all
in this place at the same time.

00:42:01.580 --> 00:42:04.180
And the right things do happen.

00:42:04.180 --> 00:42:08.200
But there's a lot of confusion
when you come out of a war.

00:42:08.200 --> 00:42:09.970
JILL PAICE: And I
think for us as actors,

00:42:09.970 --> 00:42:12.980
getting to live in Paris for
two months, and so much of Paris

00:42:12.980 --> 00:42:15.610
is preserved as it
was back in that time.

00:42:15.610 --> 00:42:19.070
So to see the very locations,
the Galleries Lafayette,

00:42:19.070 --> 00:42:22.100
the Ritz, Montmartre, things
that we reference in our show,

00:42:22.100 --> 00:42:23.370
to go and see them.

00:42:23.370 --> 00:42:26.820
We also happened to be there
when the Musee Carnavalet was

00:42:26.820 --> 00:42:30.240
doing this amazing photography
exhibit on the liberation

00:42:30.240 --> 00:42:32.360
and on the resistance fighters.

00:42:32.360 --> 00:42:36.600
So we all went, all of us,
and spent a day there, sort

00:42:36.600 --> 00:42:39.550
of absorbing this experience.

00:42:39.550 --> 00:42:42.330
And I think more than
anything, being there

00:42:42.330 --> 00:42:46.160
made sure that we didn't make a
character of their experience.

00:42:46.160 --> 00:42:48.420
So it became very real to us.

00:42:48.420 --> 00:42:51.806
And we were very well received
by the French audiences, which,

00:42:51.806 --> 00:42:54.180
we weren't sure when we went
there what it would be like.

00:42:54.180 --> 00:42:57.290
And our first sort of
run through in front

00:42:57.290 --> 00:43:00.330
of an invited audience was
flabbergasting, because they

00:43:00.330 --> 00:43:01.240
were on their feet.

00:43:01.240 --> 00:43:04.260
And you look over, and the crew
were clapping in the wings.

00:43:04.260 --> 00:43:07.620
And we just felt so
embraced by this culture

00:43:07.620 --> 00:43:08.620
and by these people.

00:43:08.620 --> 00:43:11.950
I have a real
affection for them now.

00:43:11.950 --> 00:43:13.627
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:43:13.627 --> 00:43:14.710
FEMALE SPEAKER: Thank you.

00:43:14.710 --> 00:43:15.670
A question over here?

00:43:15.670 --> 00:43:16.370
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:43:16.370 --> 00:43:17.720
I loved this show.

00:43:17.720 --> 00:43:19.890
It was one of my favorite
shows I've ever seen.

00:43:19.890 --> 00:43:21.520
And I also love the ballet.

00:43:21.520 --> 00:43:24.440
I actually was at Lincoln
Center last night.

00:43:24.440 --> 00:43:27.210
And I really care about
the ballet as an art form,

00:43:27.210 --> 00:43:30.110
and I care about the fact
that the audience is aging.

00:43:30.110 --> 00:43:32.031
And one of my hopes
for the show would

00:43:32.031 --> 00:43:33.530
be, seeing how
popular it is, and it

00:43:33.530 --> 00:43:36.491
won the Tony, is that it can
expand the exposure that ballet

00:43:36.491 --> 00:43:38.115
is getting with the
general population,

00:43:38.115 --> 00:43:42.340
and perhaps raise the profile
and attendance of the ballet.

00:43:42.340 --> 00:43:43.930
And I just wonder
if that's something

00:43:43.930 --> 00:43:46.260
you guys have talked about,
if you planned for that,

00:43:46.260 --> 00:43:47.780
if there's anything.

00:43:47.780 --> 00:43:49.363
CHRISTOPHER WHEELDON:
I think, I mean,

00:43:49.363 --> 00:43:54.550
it was certainly a
very attractive reason

00:43:54.550 --> 00:43:59.450
to do this show, for me,
was to put some real ballet

00:43:59.450 --> 00:44:03.400
on Broadway, and put
it out for an audience

00:44:03.400 --> 00:44:06.050
that perhaps hasn't had the
opportunity to go to the ballet

00:44:06.050 --> 00:44:07.800
before, or as I said
before, may have

00:44:07.800 --> 00:44:09.840
some sort of preconceived
notion that it's

00:44:09.840 --> 00:44:12.010
stuffy or old fashioned.

00:44:12.010 --> 00:44:17.110
I have to say that for
me, the joy and confidence

00:44:17.110 --> 00:44:20.140
that I get from
hearing the biggest

00:44:20.140 --> 00:44:21.860
ovation of the
night, every night,

00:44:21.860 --> 00:44:25.390
on Broadway, for a non-ballet
audience, be for the ballet,

00:44:25.390 --> 00:44:27.660
and hear the comments of
the audience as they leave.

00:44:27.660 --> 00:44:30.120
Sometimes I lurk,
which can be dangerous,

00:44:30.120 --> 00:44:32.840
because sometimes you
hear bad things, too.

00:44:32.840 --> 00:44:35.763
But hearing people
say, oh, you know,

00:44:35.763 --> 00:44:37.596
I didn't know ballet
could be that exciting.

00:44:40.300 --> 00:44:42.847
Or just having notes
left for me saying,

00:44:42.847 --> 00:44:45.430
we're really excited to come see
you work at the New York City

00:44:45.430 --> 00:44:48.700
Ballet, or go see the ballet
at American Ballet Theater.

00:44:48.700 --> 00:44:50.510
It's really encouraging.

00:44:50.510 --> 00:44:52.090
And I think we're lucky.

00:44:52.090 --> 00:44:54.890
I think we're part
of a generation where

00:44:54.890 --> 00:44:57.200
the audience for ballet
is being reinvigorated.

00:44:57.200 --> 00:44:58.990
There are, now,
young choreographers

00:44:58.990 --> 00:45:02.260
who are excited about
making dynamic ballet again.

00:45:02.260 --> 00:45:08.090
And ballet that focuses
on the human condition

00:45:08.090 --> 00:45:11.410
and a connection between people.

00:45:11.410 --> 00:45:15.800
It went through a period of
this sort of intensely physical,

00:45:15.800 --> 00:45:18.240
it became very much about
what the body could do.

00:45:18.240 --> 00:45:20.160
And now I think
it's veering back

00:45:20.160 --> 00:45:27.114
towards a more narrative base,
which is very, very exciting.

00:45:27.114 --> 00:45:28.530
And particularly
here in New York,

00:45:28.530 --> 00:45:30.220
I think [? our ballet ?]
incentive

00:45:30.220 --> 00:45:32.652
has a lot of really, really
exciting new work going on.

00:45:32.652 --> 00:45:34.110
AUDIENCE: It would
be neat if there

00:45:34.110 --> 00:45:36.872
was a promotion for the ballet,
for the audience as they

00:45:36.872 --> 00:45:38.080
leave your show or something.

00:45:38.080 --> 00:45:38.800
CHRISTOPHER WHEELDON: Yeah.

00:45:38.800 --> 00:45:41.110
LEANNE COPE: We were at
the Broadway flea market

00:45:41.110 --> 00:45:42.792
the other day, and
this guy came up.

00:45:42.792 --> 00:45:45.292
We were signing posters, and
