00:46:54.700 --> 00:46:56.700
And I'd love to hear you
talk a little bit about

00:46:56.700 --> 00:46:59.800
how your experiences
with the NYCB

00:46:59.800 --> 00:47:01.740
informed your work
with the show,

00:47:01.740 --> 00:47:04.172
and maybe what the
differences and the challenges

00:47:04.172 --> 00:47:05.880
are that you face
working in pure ballet,

00:47:05.880 --> 00:47:06.969
versus a Broadway show.

00:47:06.969 --> 00:47:09.260
CHRISTOPHER WHEELDON: Well,
actually, it's interesting.

00:47:09.260 --> 00:47:13.030
I think my experiences working
with the New York City Ballet

00:47:13.030 --> 00:47:17.240
as a dancer and a choreographer,
and also with the Royal Ballet,

00:47:17.240 --> 00:47:21.570
in our show, for me, it's
almost the coming together

00:47:21.570 --> 00:47:27.320
of my two balletic
worlds, my upbringing,

00:47:27.320 --> 00:47:31.620
my training in London, in
sort of a more narrative based

00:47:31.620 --> 00:47:32.200
works.

00:47:32.200 --> 00:47:34.491
You know, the Royal Ballet
are famous for the big story

00:47:34.491 --> 00:47:35.510
ballets.

00:47:35.510 --> 00:47:38.990
And for such a small
country, we actually

00:47:38.990 --> 00:47:44.160
had two of the great, great
narrative ballet choreographers

00:47:44.160 --> 00:47:46.680
that ever lived, Sir Frederick
Ashton and Sir Kenneth

00:47:46.680 --> 00:47:50.470
MacMillan, creating works
for the Royal Ballet.

00:47:50.470 --> 00:47:53.656
So I grew up in that
world, like Leanne,

00:47:53.656 --> 00:47:55.030
and then I moved
to New York when

00:47:55.030 --> 00:47:57.510
I was 19 because I wanted
something different.

00:47:57.510 --> 00:48:01.700
And I'd had a chance to dance in
a ballet by George Balanchine.

00:48:01.700 --> 00:48:05.110
And it was the first
time, it was liberating.

00:48:05.110 --> 00:48:07.800
It was for my school
performance in London.

00:48:07.800 --> 00:48:10.570
Suddenly I was just
kind of thrust out

00:48:10.570 --> 00:48:14.800
onto the stage, and just
really devouring space,

00:48:14.800 --> 00:48:17.645
and it was the music
that was driving me.

00:48:17.645 --> 00:48:18.520
There wasn't a story.

00:48:18.520 --> 00:48:21.490
It was just really purely about
sort of an emotional response

00:48:21.490 --> 00:48:22.740
to music.

00:48:22.740 --> 00:48:26.610
So that encouraged me
to move to New York,

00:48:26.610 --> 00:48:29.430
and I built my
choreographic career

00:48:29.430 --> 00:48:32.550
really learning from the inside
of these great Balanchine

00:48:32.550 --> 00:48:35.910
and Robbins works, and the
works also of Jerome Robbins.

00:48:35.910 --> 00:48:40.240
So having the chance to kind of
bring those two worlds together

00:48:40.240 --> 00:48:44.720
and put them on the stage
in this beautiful show,

00:48:44.720 --> 00:48:46.510
I feel like I was
able to really draw

00:48:46.510 --> 00:48:49.450
from both of those experiences.

00:48:52.140 --> 00:48:56.390
ROBERT FAIRCHILD: I
feel like for me, it's

00:48:56.390 --> 00:48:59.120
been whar-- I've had
the opportunity three

00:48:59.120 --> 00:49:02.472
times in the past two weeks to
go dance back with the New York

00:49:02.472 --> 00:49:04.430
City Ballet, because that
was kind of the deal.

00:49:04.430 --> 00:49:07.010
My boss said, well, I'll let
you go on Broadway for a year

00:49:07.010 --> 00:49:09.660
if you come back and dance
for me every once in awhile.

00:49:09.660 --> 00:49:13.760
So I had three
shows, and honestly,

00:49:13.760 --> 00:49:18.110
what I've learned from doing
Broadway and this show,

00:49:18.110 --> 00:49:22.510
and telling stories,
has informed everything

00:49:22.510 --> 00:49:24.720
about my dancing in a
completely different way.

00:49:24.720 --> 00:49:28.380
I go back on that stage,
and my thought process

00:49:28.380 --> 00:49:30.140
is completely different.

00:49:30.140 --> 00:49:31.860
Whether there's a
story or there's not,

00:49:31.860 --> 00:49:33.670
there's something
happening in my brain.

00:49:33.670 --> 00:49:35.160
There's something
being told, and I

00:49:35.160 --> 00:49:40.140
think that's why ballet can
become unrelatable sometimes,

00:49:40.140 --> 00:49:43.070
is because people
don't relate themselves

00:49:43.070 --> 00:49:45.660
to who they are in
the moment, as people,

00:49:45.660 --> 00:49:48.110
and put that into their dancing.

00:49:48.110 --> 00:49:52.120
And when we get to
do that in the show,

00:49:52.120 --> 00:49:55.120
the dance is a real part
of the storytelling.

00:49:55.120 --> 00:50:00.610
It's these people, when words
can't describe your feeling,

00:50:00.610 --> 00:50:03.470
song can't describe your
feeling, but movement does.

00:50:03.470 --> 00:50:06.260
And that's something
so incredible to get

00:50:06.260 --> 00:50:08.990
to learn through this
show, and then, to bring

00:50:08.990 --> 00:50:12.800
that back to New York
City Ballet, and just

00:50:12.800 --> 00:50:14.910
kind of permeate that world
with what we're doing,

00:50:14.910 --> 00:50:17.114
is just so incredible.

